# Django Guidance

## Project Context

- Django version: {{ django_version | default("detected by Akira") }}
- Settings module: {{ settings_module | default("project settings") }}
- API layer: {{ api_layer | default("Django views or DRF if detected") }}

## Project Structure

- Keep domain behavior close to the app that owns the model.
- Put URL routing in app-level `urls.py` files when the project uses them.
- Keep settings explicit and split by environment only when already established.
- Use management commands for operational tasks instead of ad hoc scripts.

## Models And Queries

- Keep model methods small and side-effect aware.
- Use `select_related()` and `prefetch_related()` for known relationship access.
- Prefer queryset methods or managers for reusable query logic.
- Keep migrations reviewable and generated from intentional model changes.

{% if uses_drf | default(false) %}
## Django REST Framework

- Keep serializers explicit about fields and validation.
- Put permission classes on views or viewsets.
- Prefer viewsets only when the resource shape fits DRF conventions.
{% endif %}

{% include "_partials/error_handling.md.j2" %}

## Testing Hooks

- Use Django's test database isolation.
- Test URLs, permissions, and serializer validation at the boundary.
- Prefer factories or fixtures over large inline setup blocks.

## Avoid

- Query logic duplicated across views.
- Unbounded queryset evaluation in templates or serializers.
- Settings reads hidden deep in domain code.
- Manual database changes outside migrations.
